<TEXT>
police in riot gear and east village residents 
faced off wednesday night after dozens of homeless people were 
evicted from tompkins square park 
the homeless were evicted because of a new city regulation took 
effect wednesday banning residential structures such as tents from 
city parks 
later hundreds of east villagerfs began surrounding the park as 
police wearing helmets with visors tried to keep the entrances to 
the park blocked 
the mood was tense but there were no immediate reports of 
widespread clashes there were some reports of bottlethrowing 
earlier about 100 people shouting its our park staged an 
impromptu march around the park as the raid got underway 
the homeless people apparently did not resist and police reported 
no arrests 
dozens of homeless people live in the park which was the site of 
a sevenhour riot last aug 7 when police tried to enforce a curfew 
that was later revoked fiftytwo police officers and 18 civilians 
required hospital treatment after the clash 115 complaints of 
police brutality were filed 
the controversial regulation that went into effect wednesday was 
proposed by the department of parks and recreation and had been 
opposed by homeless people and advocates for the homeless 
alan moss a parks department deputy commissioner was at the 
park while the eviction was carried out and said this is not 
aimed at the homeless who have been using parks it is aimed at 
getting rid of permanent structures when you see a big spike being 
driven into a tree and boards being nailed together that doesnt 
belong in a park 
he said the new rule would not stop a homeless person from 
sleeping on a park bench or on the grass 
human resources administration workers were on the scene with 
vans so that those who wanted could go to city shelters 
the raid began at about 830 pm 
</TEXT>
