<TEXT>
here is a chronology of key events in the 
oliver north irancontra case from his indictment to sentencing 
1988 
march 16 north former reagan national security adviser john m 
poindexter former maj gen richard secord and iranianamerican 
arms dealer albert hakim are indicted on charges including 
conspiracy to divert iranian armssales profits to the contras 
march 18 north announces his retirement from the marine corps 
says he may subpoena the highest ranking officials in our 
government 
june 6 us district judge gerhard a gesell orders separate 
trials for the four defendants independent counsel lawrence e 
walsh the next day says north will go first 
nov 7 one of 16 criminal counts against north fabricating a 
document is dismissed 
nov 21 gesell says that if north stands trial the court will 
have little control over the testimony of witnesses acquainted 
with high security matters he appeals to president reagan to 
decide whether the government will allow the trial to take place 
nov 29 gesell refuses to dismiss two of the central charges 
against north conspiracy to defraud the government and theft of 
government property he dismisses one wire fraud 
dec 1 reagan rules out a north pardon but says duty 
requires his administration to block release of secret documents 
north wants for his trial 
dec 12 gesell tells north he cant use 3500 secret documents 
that he can use more than 300 roughly the same number planned to be 
introduced by the prosecution the decision removes a major obstacle 
to the trial going forward 
dec 30 north subpoenas reagan and presidentelect bush as 
defense witnesses gesell after bush is sworn as president the 
following month rules he wont be called he postpones a decision 
regarding reagan 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 5 prosecutors ask gesell to dismiss conspiracy and theft 
charges citing norths insistence on introducing classified 
information in his defense and the reagan administrations refusal 
to release material the judge ruled north would need gesell later 
dismisses those counts 
twelve felony counts remain including lying to congress in 1985 
and 1986 about his efforts on behalf of the contras and lying to the 
attorney general about the national security councils role in 
diverting money from the iran arms sales 
north also is accused of illegally accepting a 13800 security 
system at his home from codefendant richard secord converting to 
his own use at least 4300 in travelers checks from contra leader 
adolfo calero and conspiring to defraud the government of tax 
revenue by using a taxexempt foundation to funnel money to the 
contras 
jan 31 jury selection begins 
feb 8 the justice department interrupts norths trial urging 
new safeguards to prevent him from making surprise disclosures of 
classified information gesell denies the request 
feb 9 a jury of nine women and three men is selected 
feb 10 the justice department seeks again to delay norths 
trial a federal appeals court panel denies the request 
feb 12 chief justice william h rehnquist grants a delay until 
the full supreme court can consider the justice departments 
objections to the release of classified material by norths defense 
feb 15 the justice department issues guidelines designed to 
guard against disclosure of certain classified material by north 
feb 16 the supreme court lifts its stay 
feb 21 the trial opens with prosecutor john keker portraying 
north as a liar who places himself above the law and defense 
lawyer brendan sullivan calling him a patriotic marine who obeyed 
the orders of his commanderinchief 
march 8 fundraiser carl channell testifies that north once 
said of his work for the contras i dont care if i have to go to 
jail for this i dont care if i have to lie to congress 
march 15 former national security adviser robert mcfarlane 
testifies that reagan approved a secret arrangement under which 
honduras got military aid for supporting the contras 
march 21 security consultant glenn robinette testifies that 
north let secord pay for a security fence at his home and then tried 
to cover up the deal after he left the white house 
march 23 fawn hall norths secretary at the white house 
tearfully testifies that he was a tireless and selfless boss and 
their shredding of irancontra documents was no big deal 
march 28 former attorney general edwin meese iii testifies 
administration officials were worried about impeachment of reagan 
after they discovered the irancontra link 
march 31 gesell rejects norths request that he order reagan to 
testify saying there is no proof the former president authorized 
north to commit crimes 
april 6 the defense introduces an admission of facts agreed to 
by the government stating that george bush as vice president met 
with honduran president suazo to tell him of expedited aid the 
document says the aid was in return for honduras help to the 
contras 
north takes the stand saying he was merely a marine following 
white house orders 
april 7 north concedes he lied to the house intelligence 
committee at an aug 6 1986 meeting at the white house at which he 
denied providing assistance to the contras 
april 12 north testifies he thought he was protecting reagan 
when he altered irancontra memos before investigators from the 
justice department could get a look at them 
april 13 north leaves the stand the defense rests 
april 18 prosecutor keker in a hardhitting summation says 
north and mcfarlane were following adolf hitlers old strategy 
which is the victor will never be asked if he told the truth 
april 19 in an emotional closing argument sullivan says north 
became a sacrificial lamb in the reagan white house and was 
fired to spare the former president political harm 
bush tells reporters at the white house that my conscience is 
clear about the irancontra affair 
april 21 the jury begins deliberations 
may 4 north is convicted of falsifying and destroying 
documents accepting an illegal gratuity and aiding and abetting in 
the obstruction of congress he was acquitted of five other counts 
of lying to or obstructing congress of lying to meese of illegally 
converting travelers checks to his own use and of conspiring to 
defraud the irs 
june 30 gesell denies a mistrial motion filed by the defense on 
grounds that juror tara leigh king had falsely denied in a 
questionnaire that she or her relatives had ever been involved in a 
court proceeding or criminal investigation 
july 5 gesell sentences north to a suspended prison term and a 
150000 fine for his role in the irancontra affair north is 
placed on two years probation and ordered to perform 1200 hours of 
community service administering a new program to help innercity 
youth avoid involvement in drugs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

