<TEXT>
secretary of state james a 
baker iii adjusting us policy to changing realities said today 
that the vietnamesebacked government in cambodia is entitled to a 
central role in efforts to reach a political settlement there 
baker endorsed efforts by resistance leader prince norodom 
sihanouk and government leader hun sen to reach agreement on 
cambodias political future once vietnam completes its promised 
troop pullout in september 
he called this effort crucial to the achievement of a viable 
political accord 
bakers speech before foreign ministers of the association of 
southeast asian nations marked a subtle shift in the evolving us 
policy toward cambodia as vietnam prepares to complete its 
withdrawal 
for years the united states focused on a complete vietnamese 
pullout deriding hun sen and his allies as hanois puppets 
with withdrawal now close the bush administration is 
increasingly concerned that the khmer rouge militarily the 
strongest of three cambodian resistance factions could fill the 
vacuum left by the departing vietnamese 
for baker there is no higher priority in southeast asia than 
blocking the return to power of the khmer rouge which during its 
197578 rule killed hundreds of thousands as it tried to turn 
cambodia into an agrarian commune 
the vietnamese invaded in late 1978 forcing out the khmer rouge 
baker spelled out the type of agreement he believes would be 
appropriate for cambodia a ceasefire cessation of foreign 
military aid to all factions an interim coalition government led by 
sihanouk and an international presence to oversee free elections 
france has indicated an interest in playing host to a conference 
of the four factions that will vie for power in the aftermath of the 
vietnamese withdrawal 
with us support the asean countries of indonesia thailand 
singapore malaysia the philippines and brunei have been supporting 
the two noncommunist resistance forces in cambodia 
while baker believes a return to power of the khmer rouge could 
lead to a second holocaust in cambodia sihanouks position is that 
moderate elements of the khmer rouge should be welcome to take part 
in a provisional government 
sihanouk a former cambodian head of state fears the khmer rouge 
would otherwise be encouraged to continue the struggle they have 
waged since vietnamese forces ousted them from power 
on wednesday sihanouk ruled out a separate peace agreement with 
the vietnameseinstalled government in phnom penh and promised to 
keep fighting 
he told a news conference in beijing one of his homes in exile 
that any settlement must include his khmer rouge allies 
fears of a khmer rouge takeover have prompted the first serious 
division within the united states over indochina vietnam laos and 
cambodia since us military involvement there ended 16 years ago 
the bush administration wants to send lethal aid for the first 
time to the noncommunist rebel forces in cambodia but the 
administration is encountering strong resistance in congress where 
some lawmakers worry that us weapons will fall into the hands of 
the khmer rouge 
rep stephen solarz dny has said the alternative to such aid 
might be a second asian auschwitz under khmer rouge sponsorship 
baker expressed hope that the day is near when indochina can be 
transformed from a battlefield to a marketplace 
yet to achieve this end to remake the terrible swords of the 
killing fields into plowshares for a peaceful community we must 
maintain our resolve and our unity of purpose now more than ever 
