staterun mti news agency said 
the agency said the ruling communist party had with profound 
sorrow informed its members and the hungarian people of 
comrade kadars death 
mti said funeral arrangements would be announced later it was 
considered unlikely he would be buried before president bushs visit 
next week 
hungarian television broadcast a halfhour documentary on his 
life this morning and two budapest radio stations canceled all 
programming containing rock n roll music and light entertainment 
kadar was hospitalized monday with pneumonia and severe breathing 
and circulatory problems 
he was first reported gravely ill in april and in may lost his 
post as honorary party chairman as well as a seat on the partys 
central committee which wrote him a letter criticizing mistakes 
during his lengthy rule 
since he was replaced by karoly grosz in may 1988 as party 
general secretary kadars political legacy has come under fierce 
attack and the communists have moved rapidly to embrace democratic 
change promising contested elections and a multiparty system 
after guiding hungary in the 1970s to relative prosperity and 
freedom dubbed goulash communism in the west kadar came to be 
seen as an impediment to further reform in the 1980s 
he will perhaps be most remembered for his 1962 statement to a 
rally in the industrial town of csepel those who are not against 
us are with us 
by the mid1980s hungarys economy was in a tailspin and the 
soviet union was undergoing a political rebirth under mikhail s 
gorbachev 
kadar fell out of favor in ruling circles 
in a published response may 10 that mti said was kadars last 
public statement the former leader admitted mistakes but said 
my actions were guided by good intentions 
in apparent reference to the 1958 execution of nagy and hundreds 
of others after the 1956 revolt kadar said in the letter i hope 
that future generations will assess more objectively the results 
and errors of the past 30 years 
nagys remains initially placed in an unmarked grave were 
reburied in a governmentsanctioned ceremony june 16 that drew 
hundreds of thousands of mourners marked his de facto political 
rehabilitation 
kadars change in fortunes was typical of a long career that 
began in 1931 when he joined the illegal communist party as a 
19yearold from a peasant background with only eight years of 
schooling 
kadar was jailed and seemingly forgotten after a party purge in 
1951 but was rehabilitated after the downfall of his stalinist 
rival matyas rakosi 
while in power kadar was conciliatory and ruthless by turns 
in an interview with the associated press in 1965 he made a 
prophetic comment you have strummed a string to the effect that 
when the monolithic unity of the communist countries is ended what 
is left 
kadar was born may 26 1912 in the adriatic port of fiume which 
was renamed rijeka and became part of yugoslavia when the 
austrohungarian empire broke up 
he advanced through communist party ranks to central committee 
membership in may 1942 having spent more than three years in prison 
on various political charges 
after the communist takeover in 1948 kadar became interior 
minister in rakosis stalinist regime but it was never clear whether 
he controlled the feared political police 
rakosi kept a jealous eye on kadars progress and had him 
arrested in 1951 on charges of espionage and treason when stalin 
died in 1953 rakosis grip on power began to slip kadar was freed 
and rehabilitated the next year 
growing discontent led to rakosis ouster in july 1956 but 
dissatisfaction continued and a popular uprising began within three 
months tens of thousands of students filled the streets demanding 
a free press withdrawal of soviet troops and a multiparty politics 
kadar became party leader a few days later left the capital and 
announced that he had established a rival government to that of 
premier nagy 
on nov 3 he asked the kremlin to help end the revolt 
red army forces moved in and kadar instituted two years of 
repression nagy and his associates were executed in june 1958 
less than four months after nagys death kadar embarked on 
economic reform that brought growing prosperity and increasingly 
cordial ties with the west 
a reticent man who liked chess and reading kadar has been 
described as a sad ascetic man with an intense face a 
dedicated hunter he told the ap hunting trips with soviet leader 
nikita khrushchev were no diplomatic pretexts for me 
if you enter a wood even as much as a meter speech stops he 
said you dont make a noise you dont talk in the woods there 
is silence that is why i like it 
kadar played a shadowy role in the shortlived czechoslovak 
liberalization of 1968 it was said that he opposed intervention in 
czechoslovakia but hungarian soldiers joined the sovietled 
invasion 
his reforms in the 1970s foreshadowed the modernization 
gorbachev now is pursuing in the soviet union less central 
planning more competition and weeding out or streamlining of 
unprofitable state concerns 
economic problems increased however by the late 1980s 
inflation was 18 percent and the foreign debt 18 billion the 
highest per capita in the soviet bloc large price increases and 
other austerity measures fed discontent and the perception that 
kadar was largely to blame 
eight months after grosz replaced kadar parliament legalized 
independent political movements 
and this year the party decided the 1956 revolt was a popular 
uprising not the counterrevolution it had been called for 33 years 
on june 16 nagys remains were reburied with honor 
in a serialized interview with the weekly magyarorszag kadar 
said nagys tragedy is my own personal tragedy as well 
he is survived by his wife maria 
</TEXT>
