two bombs exploded thursday hours before 
the firing of the traditional midday rocket that marked the start of 
the weeklong fiesta of the running of the bulls police said 
the bombs which caused no injuries wrecked the cars of two 
politicians who belong to the popular union party widely believed 
to be the political arm of the basque separatist group eta a police 
spokesman said no group claimed responsibility for the blast 
seven hours after the early morning explosions thousands in the 
citys main square cheered as officials fired off the traditional 
rocket or chupinazo to start the annual san fermin festival 
made famous by ernest hemingway in his 1926 novel the sun also 
rises 
eta whose initials stand for basque homeland and liberty has 
killed more than 600 people since it began its violent campaign for 
independence for the northern threeprovince basque region in 1968 
pamplona is the capital of the autonomous region of navarre 
which borders the basque region eta also seeks the annexation of 
navarre as an independent basque state 
the citys population of 200000 was expected to double as 
thousands of tourists arrive to partake in eight days of 
aroundtheclock festivities in honor of san fermin pamplonas 
patron saint 
the fiesta revolves around the daily morning run of bulls from a 
pen along a halfmile route to the city bull ring when hundreds of 
people try to keep ahead of the six bulls and six steers that 
accompany them 
the runs begin friday and continue through july 14 the six bulls 
reappear later in the day at a bullfight 
the festival has been held continuously since 1591 since that 
date bulls have gored 52 people to death 13 of them since 1924 
this year the city plans to spend 583000 on the festival 
including 67000 on fireworks 
on tuesday suspected basque separatists fired three 
rocketpropelled grenades at a pamplona barracks of the paramilitary 
civil guard slightly damaging the building but causing no injuries 
in 1985 an eta bomb injured a policeman in pamplona as the fiesta 
was set to start 
