the states highest court today struck down a 
new york city law designed to help the homeless by forcing owners of 
oneroom apartments to rent them out 
the court of appeals ruled 52 ruled that the fiveyear 
moratorium on redevelopment of singleroom occupancy hotels was an 
unlawful taking of private property 
no one minimizes the tragic reality of homelessness said 
judge stewart hancock jr but the citys response to foist its 
responsibility on certain private property owners by requiring them 
to remain in the sro business or ransom their property rights 
simply does not meet the requirements of the city and state 
constitutions 
in a dissent judge joseph bellacosa complained about property 
rights being held more important than social policy he recalled 
that past courts struck down child labor laws because they hurt 
business 
the 1985 new york city law prevents owners from demolishing sro 
hotels unless they pay 45000 a room into a fund to try to save 
housing for the poor elderly and sick 
the city said its goal of trying to save 52000 apartments and 
not forcing residents out into the street justified such measures 
but the appeals court overturning a lowercourt ruling said the 
law requires property owners to surrender the most basic 
attributes of private property the rights of possession and 
exclusion 
the court noted that the city spent much of the 1970s trying to 
get sro owners to tear down housing it considered a blight about 
40000 rooms were demolished to make way for office buildings and 
housing for the rich 
