gov mario cuomo has signed a law that gives 
the nations secondlargest state one of the most sweeping sets of 
restrictions on smoking in public places and at work 
the law will prohibit smoking in auditoriums elevators 
gymnasiums food stores shared taxicabs and limousines smoking 
will be restricted to certain areas in restaurants bowling alleys 
bingo halls hospitals theaters indoor arenas banks waiting 
areas and restrooms 
the clean indoor air act will we hope save lives said 
cuomo at a billsigning ceremony wednesday 
in the workplace smoking will be prohibited in a work area at an 
employees request nonsmoking areas will have to be provided in 
employee cafeterias lunch rooms and lounges to meet employee 
demand up to 70 percent although more would be possible 
smoking in theater viewing areas libraries museums and mass 
transit has long been prohibited in new york 
the smoking law wouldnt apply in bars hotel rooms conventions 
private residences private limousines private automobiles private 
parties tobacco stores and private boxes at indoor arenas such as 
luxury boxes at sports stadiums violators will be subject to fines 
of up to 1000 
businesses could also get an exemption if they could prove the 
smoking ban would create a financial hardship 
the law takes effect in early january except for the workplace 
provisions which take effect in early april 
some 41 other states have some sort of smoking restrictions but 
only minnesota has a statewide law thats tougher than new yorks 
according to the washington dcbased tobacco free america project 
california the nations largest state has a patchwork of statewide 
laws that are collectively weaker than new yorks new statute the 
group said 
