compared to the mania that greeted the soviet president in bonn 
the french were described as more skeptical the twoday visit was 
one of long private talks with president francois mitterrand and 
intimate meals with french officials not highprofile street 
diplomacy 
as expected the high point of the trip was the speech delivered 
thursday gorbachevs last day in france before the council of 
europe in strasbourg he offered additional and rapid cuts in the 
soviet nuclear arsenal if nato accepts negotiations on tactical 
nuclear weapons 
political observers say the reserved reaction of the french 
public can be traced in part to the national character 
french crowds simply tend to be less demonstrative than german 
ones said dominique moisi of the french institute of 
international relations 
politics and history also shaped the french response west 
germans view gorbachev as the source of changes that could lead to a 
reunified germany they also see the kremlin not the west as the 
best hope for getting missiles off their soil 
the french expect much less of him and are more skeptical of 
changes taking place in the soviet union moisi said 
france no longer plays the pivotal role in international 
diplomacy it did under gen charles de gaulle who took france out 
of natos unified military command and welcomed soviet courting as a 
way of irritating the united states 
in recent years france has become a defender of the atlantic 
alliance 
french intellectuals many of whom surrendered their leftist 
sympathies a decade ago gave gorbachev a lukewarm welcome when he 
spoke at the sorbonne 
nonetheless a poll published by bvaparis match before the visit 
showed that gorbachev enjoyed greater popularity with the french 
than did president bush or british prime minister margaret thatcher 
sixtysix percent of those polled had a good opinion of 
gorbachev and 59 percent believed he was sincere in trying to reform 
the soviet union 
fiftytwo percent also believed gorbachevs hold on power was 
fragile compared with 82 percent of west germans surveyed who 
