<TEXT>
janos kadar hungarys leader from the 
repression of 1956 through the liberalized goulash communism of 
the 1970s until his removal last year as a relic of the rigid past 
died thursday at age 77 
the era kadar represented we were already burying while he was 
still alive a commentator said on state radio 
that era began in october 1956 when kadar took over the 
communist party and summoned soviet tanks to crushed the 
antistalinist uprising led by premier imre nagy 
nagy was executed in 1958 liberal new hungarian leaders reburied 
him with honors this spring and a few hours after kadars death the 
supreme court exonerated nagy of all charges completing his 
rehabilitation 
a statement carried by the official news agency mti announced 
with deep shock and profound sorrow that kadar had died thursday 
after a prolonged serious illness he was hospitalized monday 
with pneumonia and breathing and circulatory problems 
kadar was reported gravely ill in april and in may lost his two 
remaining posts honorary party chairman and member of the central 
committee which wrote him a letter criticizing erroneous 
decisions during his long rule 
he responded in a letter his last public statement that he 
always acted in hungarys best interests of his country but had made 
mistakes 
a statement from the party leadership thursday emphasized both 
kadars success with cautious reform and the later years 
characterized by economic stagnation and growing discontent over 
stalled reforms 
it said his declaration to a workers rally in 1962 that those 
who are not against us are with us led to a national consensus 
which is not to say that there were no mistakes and painful 
retreats but janos kadars name came to be synonymous with humanist 
socialism 
the four members of the communist party presidium led by party 
chairman rezso nyers were named as a committee to organize the 
funeral the official news agency mti said the date and place would 
be announced later 
nyers and premier miklos nemeth left for romania to attend a 
warsaw pact summit beginning friday prompting speculation that the 
funeral would be delayed until after president george bushs visit 
to hungary next week 
black flags flew on all public buildings in budapest and state 
radio played classical music television broadcast short 
documentaries of kadars life throughout the day 
since karoly grosz replaced kadar as party chief in may 1988 the 
former leader has come under fierce attack and the new leadership 
has moved rapidly to embrace democratic change promising contested 
elections and a multiparty system 
representatives of the party and opposition have begun 
negotiations on holding the first open elections since the 
communists consolidated power in 1948 
liberal policies put forth by the new leaders are similar to 
those endorsed in 1956 by nagy whom they describe as a forerunner 
of communist reform 
nagys official status began to change this year when the party 
declared the revolt was a popular uprising not the 
counterrevolution it had been called for 33 years 
in a serialized interview with the weekly magyarorszag after the 
reburial kadar was quoted as saying nagys tragedy is my own 
personal tragedy as well 
janos kadar was born may 26 1912 in the adriatic port of fiume 
which was renamed rijeka and became part of yugoslavia when the 
austrohungarian empire broke up he joined the illegal communist 
party in 1931 as a 19yearold of peasant stock with only eight 
years of schooling 
he achieved central committee membership in may 1942 having 
spent more than three years in prison on various political charges 
when the communists took over kadar became interior minister in 
matyas rakosis stalinist regime but it was never clear whether he 
controlled the feared political police 
rakosi had him arrested in 1951 on charges of espionage and 
treason but when josef stalin died in 1953 rakosis grip on power 
began to slip kadar was freed and rehabilitated the next year 
growing discontent led to rakosis ouster in july 1956 but 
dissatisfaction continued and a popular uprising began within three 
months tens of thousands of students filled the streets demanding 
a free press withdrawal of soviet troops and multiparty politics 
kadar became party leader a few days later on nov 3 he asked 
the kremlin to help end the revolt and the red army moved in 
less than four months after nagys death kadar embarked on 
economic reform that brought growing prosperity and increasingly 
cordial ties with the west 
he was a reticent man fond of chess reading and hunting 
of hunting kadar said once if you enter a wood even as much 
as a meter speech stops you dont make a noise you dont talk in 
the woods there is silence that is why i like it 
</TEXT>
