<TEXT>
the army announced thursday that its fleet of 
ah64 attack helicopters could begin flying again after an 
investigation showed a fatal accident last week was caused by a 
piece of improperly stored sheet metal striking the tail rotor 
the army has 486 apaches its newest and most sophisticated 
helicopter gunship 
the fleet was grounded monday for the investigation into the june 
29 crash in northern florida of a national guard apache the 
copilot was killed and the pilot seriously injured when the tail 
rotor came off the helicopter 
in a statement at the pentagon the army said the investigation 
into the florida crash revealed that the tail rotor damage was 
caused by a foreign object striking a rotor blade 
physical and chemical evidence found that a piece of sheet metal 
used to help secure a door had been improperly stored and that the 
piece of metal became dislodged and flew into the ah64s tail 
rotor system the statement said 
army spokesman lt col john chapla said the rectangular piece of 
metal is about six to eight inches long and is supposed to be 
securely stored during flight 
it blew free and struck the rotor chapla said 
the investigation was conducted at the army safety center in fort 
rucker ala 
the apache fleet was last grounded in august 1987 when 
investigators studied the failure of one component of the tail 
rotor it was also grounded twice in 1986 for relatively minor 
problems 
the choppers built by mcdonnel douglas corp cost roughly 13 
million each 
the armys fleet was dealt a blow last month after dozens were 
put out of service because of damage they suffered during a freak 
wind storm at fort hood texas 
the gunship is designed to replace the cobra helicopter as the 
armys primary attack helicopter the twinengined machine which is 
designed to destroy enemy tanks carries hellfire and hydra 7 
missiles and a 30mm cannon 
