industrywide ramifications 
us district court judge edward harrington ruled that acushnet 
and its titleist division infringed on spaldings patent for a 
surlyn blend used in the companys top selling ball top flite 
the ruling wednesday could affect the rest of the golf ball 
industry because spaldings attorney george mcandrews said that 
the company intends to move ahead with patent lawsuits against 
virtually all the golf ball makers in the country 
spalding filed the lawsuit against acushnet in 1981 the two 
companies control about 80 percent of the golf ball market with 
spalding the leader 
mcandrews refused to tell the boston herald the amount of damages 
spalding would seek from acushnet but he did say that it would be 
a significant portion of acushnets profits on balls that 
infringed on spalding patents 
they had hundreds of millions of dollars in sales on those 
balls he said well now try to determine what portion of that 
was profit 
a spokesman for acushnet said the decision would not affect the 
companys daytoday operations 
were disputing the decision and well appeal it said wally 
uihlein president and chief executive officer of acushnets 
titleist division 
uihlein told the newspaper that the company stopped using the 
surlyn blend four years ago 
this decision has no effect on our daytoday operations he 
said we converted our balls in 1985 and converted again 
recently we maintain a pretty healthy balance sheet 
