<TEXT>
a favorable court ruling has prompted 
spalding worldwide sports inc to seek millions of dollars in 
damages from competitors that it says have illegally copied its 
patented golf ball covering 
spalding the nations biggest golf ball maker filed suits 
against three other major golf ball manufacturers immediately after 
a judge on wednesday upheld its patent infringment claim against 
rival acushnet co robert k adikes spaldings general counsel 
said thursday 
at issue in the case was a golf ball covering spalding had 
patented and which the company claims is illegally used by 95 
percent of the industry 
spalding which filed suit against acushnet in 1981 has pending 
suits against macgregor sporting goods inc and wilson sporting 
goods co another golf ball maker ram settled for an undisclosed 
sum in 1986 
wally uihlein president and chief executive officer of acushnet 
said the company planned to appeal us district judge edward f 
harringtons decision 
its a very very complex patent issue uihlein said its 
a classic case where somebody may look at a glass of water and see 
it as half full and someone else might look at it as half empty 
acushnet agreed to stop using the disputed process on its golf 
balls in 1986 pending the outcome of spaldings suit 
adikes declined to say how much spalding would seek in damages at 
a separate hearing to be scheduled following acushnets appeal 
however he estimated that the interest charges alone would reach 
into the millions of dollars 
spalding which makes topflite balls and acushnet which 
markets the titleist line control about 80 percent of the 500 
millionayear golf ball market 
adikes said the only manufacturers not now using the spalding 
process are achusnet and ram 
robert molitor spaldings vice president for research developed 
the method of coating golf balls with a blend of plastic surlyn 
resins in 1971 
originally our aim was to make the ball more durable and 
resistent to cracking in the cold said tom mayer director of 
marketing for spalding it did that but then we discovered it 
also added increased distance and we immediately patented it 
spaldings 17year patent issued in 1974 expires in 1991 
no one could find anything that worked as well so everyone else 
started copying the process in the 1980s he said 
</TEXT>
