<TEXT>
mci telecommunications inc has won a contract 
potentially worth up to 20 million over two years to provide 
longdistance telephone service to the legislative branch officials 
said thursday 
sen wendell ford dky chairman of the senate rules committee 
and rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the house 
administration committee selected mci based on recommendations from 
a team that included staff from the architect of the capitols 
office 
mci was chosen over us sprint and the american telephone amp 
telegraph co in a competitive bidding process said dan hanlon a 
spokesman for the architect the final contract should be awarded 
within three months he said 
the selection boosts the fortunes of mci a washingtonbased 
company which was part of a team that lost its bid to provide 
longdistance service to the rest of the government 
the general services administraton awarded that business 
potentially worth 25 billion over ten years to atampt and us 
sprint in december 1988 
pam small a mci spokesman said thursdays decision was a very 
important contract for mci that underscores the companys ability 
to do business with the government 
mci will replace a system in which several companies have 
provided longdistance service to the legislative branch comprised 
of the senate the house the library of congress the general 
accounting office the government printing office and congressional 
budget office and the office of technology assessment 
hanlon said the contract will cost between 5 million and 10 
million annually a savings of nearly half for the legislative 
branch longdistance service now costs between 20 million and 30 
million a year he said 
the initial contract will be for two years which options for 
renewal 
